TEXT: Good morning, everyone.
My name is Ben Spincer, and on behalf of Telstra I'd like to welcome you to our full year results for financial year 2012.
I'd like to welcome those of you here in Melbourne, those of you listening on the phone, and those on the webcast.
Without further ado, I will hand over to the Chief Executive, David Thodey, to run you through the results.
Thanks, Ben, and let me add my welcome to you all; good to see you here this morning.
Well, the full year '12 results, what we thought we'd do today is go through three things.
I'm going to give you a brief introduction just on the highlights of the year, then I'm glad to have Andy Penn, our CFO, here and he's going to take you through the numbers in more detail.
Then I'll come back and give you a bit of an update on the big strategic priorities we've been working on, and how I see those going.
So the year in review.
Well, we've had a strong year, and I'm delighted to say we've delivered on our commitments.
We've met the guidance that we set 12 months ago, and we've delivered total revenue of AUD25.4 billion.
On a guidance basis, total revenue increased by 1.3%, and EBITDA was up 2.1%.
I'm very pleased to say the business has proved resilient in very mixed economic conditions, and when you go through the results there's some real highlights.
We had top and bottom line growth, which is so important in terms of profitable revenue growth.
We've won share in all our major product categories.
Also, we've grown profitability across all our key products, which is so important.

And very importantly, as you know, we had the declines in Sensis and in Telstra business, and the rest of the domestic Telco business has been able to pick up those declines and offset them in the year.
Also, our balance sheet remains very strong, and we really do now have a very clear capital management strategy that Andy will talk to as well.

So our strategic priorities are really starting to deliver results; improving customer service; growing and retaining the number of our customers; simplifying the business; taking the complexity out of the business; and also, finding new growth portfolios that will be so important for us in the future.
What I thought I'd do, before I throw it to Andy, is just reflect on what I think have been really the four key highlights for me, personally, through the year.
There's no question, when I look back over the 12 months, it's been an eventful year; in fact, it's hard to imagine it was nine months ago when we went to shareholders on the NBN transaction.
A lot has happened in the last 12 months.
But let me just give you my four highlights.
Firstly, our focus on putting the customer at the center of everything we do, as easy as that is to say, is starting to make a difference.
I want to stress, this is as much a cultural change within a company like Telstra as it is about changing the way we really run the business.
There's been a lot of efforts right across the business to do that, because it's not just an attitude; you've got to really get down into the core part of the business.

When you look at some of the internal and the external measures, it's encouraging to see the changes, things like number of TIO complaints, the activation in terms of activating services, and also restoring them when we've got a problem, have all shown significant improvements.
The number of billing enquiries have done down significantly; we had shop and online improvement.
You see it's a vast array of things we have to do to actually change the way that customers talk about Telstra, and we are starting to make progress.

Then, we've taken a significant step, that I probably would say is not as well understood by the market, is moving to the this thing called Net Promoter System, where you are really driven by giving a customer an experience that they say, hey, you should try it, and that is a big change for a company like Telstra.
We really want to turn customers into advocates for Telstra not just to say, well, it was an okay service.
So that's been encouraging, but we still have a long way to go, and I am very clear that we have not delivered anywhere near where we'd like to be.

The second achievement is our mobiles performance, both in terms of the growth in the number of subscribers, the revenue growth, and also, importantly, the quality of our network that really reflects the outstanding engineering capability we have in this Company.
We added 1.6 million domestic mobile customers; that means we're now at 13.8 million customers.
This includes 6.6 million postpaid handheld, 3.3 million prepaid handheld, and now 3.1 million mobile broadband customers.
That's outstanding results.
We also, very pleasingly, had 475,000 new mobile customers in Hong Kong, bringing  the total number on our CSL network to 3.5 million customers.
Also, as I said, the quality of your network is really a differentiator in this game of mobility.
As you know, we improved the performance of our network by rolling out LTE.
We were the first operator really to roll it out, one of the first in the world around the 1800 spectrum.

It's one thing for us to say that we think the network's good, but when you've got companies like JD Power, Frost & Sullivan, Gizmodo, and Lifehacker, all saying that your network's very strong, that's the endorsement that we look for, and customer speak, and that's really who we look to.
So very strong result on our mobiles performance.
The third achievement is the work that we've done in relation to capital and portfolio management.
For a company like Telstra, this is very important.
As you know, it was in April that Andy took you through our capital management strategy, and I think that that's given us the discipline in the business to make the right decisions.
This is very important across all our portfolio.
You'll have seen last month that we made the decision to sell TelstraClear in New Zealand, and this is a very active part of managing the portfolio that we have as Telstra.
Lastly, and I couldn't but mention, has been the NBN negotiations, and it's great to have those agreements done with the Commonwealth and NBN Co.
Of course, the ACCC acceptance of the Structural Separation Undertaking were enormous efforts right across the business, and really have taken up a lot of time.
As I alluded to in my introductory comments, it was only just last October that we had the AGM where shareholders voted in favor of our participation of the rollout.

That was an important milestone, because for us, giving greater certainty around our future, having that behind us, is so important so we can get on and do what we enjoy doing, and that's running the business.
Also, with the NBN agreements now in place, we really are committed to delivering on those agreements, and that's our focus, very much our focus.
We are NBN ready, because we've got to leverage the opportunities that that does create for us.
As you know, in March we received AUD321 million from the Government as part of the Information Campaign and Migration Deed.
Then in June, we received another AUD100 million from the Government for the Retaining Funding Arrangement.
So these have been significant payments to us.
Also, and I'm very pleased to announce today, that we have handed over stage one of the transit network build to NBN Co.
Now remember, that's the dark fiber build, and getting all the rack spaces done for their poise.
That's been a lot of work, and we don't often talk about it, but we have a very strong and very capable team working on that.
And we are going to continue to seek opportunities to collaborate with NBN Co as they work through their rollout schedule.

We think there are some opportunities, which we are going to allude to today, to accelerate that transit build, because we think that's important in terms of the overall relationship and structure of the NBN.

Also, I'm pleased to say that we are now competing aggressively in the market with our NBN products, and as these fiber service areas are rolled out, we are really ramping up our marketing and sales efforts, and our service efforts, in competing.
I'm very pleased with some of the early results.
So they were the four highlights for me from the year.
Andy's going to take you through the financial highlights.
I must say that I'm absolutely delighted to have Andy with us on the team.
It's a great pleasure to work with him, and we think we've got some exciting days ahead of us.
So Andy, over to you.
Thank you very much, David, and good morning, everybody.
I'm going to cover five topics in my presentation this morning.
Firstly, I will take you through the Group results and comment on how we've tracked, relative to guidance.
Secondly, I will take you through the performance of our key product groups, Fixed, Mobile, Data & IP, and of course, our growth businesses NAS, Media and International.
Thirdly, I will comment on our continued progress we are making in relation to productivity improvements and efficiencies, and how these are being delivered through operating expense improvements.
Fourthly, I will provide you with an update, as David said, on our capital position against the background of the capital management framework that I announced in April.
And finally, I will conclude with some comments on the outlook for fiscal year 2013, and also guidance.
As David has already mentioned, we are pleased to have delivered another strong set of results in line with our commitments to the market, and in line with guidance.
For the financial year ended June 30, 2012, on a reported basis, revenue was up 1.1% to AUD25.4 billion.
EBITDA was 0.8% to AUD10.2 billion.
This included the AUD130 million impairment in relation to the sale of TelstraClear in New Zealand.
Earnings per share were up 5.4% to AUD0.27.5 per share.
On a guidance basis, total revenue, as David mentioned, was up 1.3%, and EBITDA was up 2.1%.
The guidance basis excludes the impact of impairments, regulated wholesale price changes, and payments received from the Government in relation to NBN.
A reconciliation of these impacts is provided in the appendix to my presentation.
Accrued capital expenditure for the year was AUD3.6 billion, or 14.2% of sales.
During the year, we generated AUD5.2 billion of free cash flow, further strengthening our capital position.
The Board has declared a final dividend of AUD0.14 per share and this brings the total dividend for the year to AUD0.28 per share, fully franked.
Looking across the businesses, reported revenue was up 1.1% to AUD25.4 billion.
Fixed revenues declined 6.1%, as expected, and like most print businesses, Sensis experienced a significant decline in print revenues this year, which was the main cause of the 9.6% decline in Media.

It is against this background, therefore, that our revenue growth was particularly pleasing with Mobile revenue up AUD679 million, or 8.5%; NAS revenue up AUD120 million, or 10.5%; and International revenue up AUD98 million, or 7%, collectively adding almost AUD1 billion of extra revenue.
Let me now take you through the performance of our products in more detail, starting with Fixed.
Total Fixed revenue declined 6.1% to AUD7.5 billion.
PSTN revenue declined 10% due to a 281,000 reduction in retail PSTN lines, and lower ARPU.
Recent research has indicated that approximately 2% of households moved to mobile-only households during the year, with the total now standing at around 14% nationally.
Partly offsetting the decline in PSTN revenue was strong growth in our Fixed retail broadband business.
Revenue was up 8.5% to AUD1.6 billion driven by strong customer growth, up 203,000 to 1.6 million (sic - see slide 6 "2.6 million").
This strong result highlights the success of our bundled strategy in particular, with continued strong growth in existing customers taking multiple products for the first time.
We now have more than 1.4 million customers on bundled plans, with 336,000 added in 2012.
We also achieved a 6 percentage point improvement in our Fixed retail broadband margin to 37%, following capital investments and productivity improvements.
Going forward, we expect the revenue mix to continue to shift from PSTN to Fixed broadband with increased penetration of bundled plans and, of course, the rollout of NBN.
There is no doubt that 2012 was a standout year for our Mobiles business.
Revenues were up 8.5% to AUD8.7 billion, and Mobiles now represent more than one-third of our total revenue base.
We continued to win market share during the year with the acquisition of a further 1.6 million Mobile customers.
These results were supported by the superiority of our networks, including the launch of our 4G network in September 2011.
We have sold more than 375,000 4G devices since the launch.
In the postpaid handheld market, customer growth was up 8.8% and revenue was up 6% to AUD4.7 billion.
ARPU declined 3.8%, mainly due to the impact of Mobile repayment option.
Excluding this, postpaid handheld ARPUs were broadly flat over the year, whilst postpaid handheld deactivation rates improved to 12.2%.
2012 has, therefore, represented another very strong year for Mobiles with EBITDA up 21% to AUD3.1 billion.
Turning to Data & IP; overall revenue declined 0.8%, however, the portfolio continued to deliver strong EBITDA margins at 64%.
IP Access revenue grew 8.9% to AUD1.1 billion as we continue to grow market share.
This was offset by declines in legacy Data products down 14.9%, and ISDN revenues down 5.8%.
IP Access continues to act as a strong platform for our Network Application Services business, NAS, in Enterprise and Government sector in particular.
NAS products such as Cloud and IP Telephony are also a platform for extending IP products into the small business sector.
In this regard, we have seen strong growth in NAS over the last couple of years, and revenue was up again, in 2012, 10.5% to AUD1.26 billion.
This was supported by strong growth in Unified Communications, up 14.4%, and Cloud computing, up 42.2%.
We saw growth in NAS across most market segments, particularly Enterprise and Government, and the large business market.
During the year we signed a number of important contracts with the Department of Human Services, Australia Post, NAB, and Origin.
These long-term, large contracts will underpin our growth in the coming years.
Looking at the core Australian Telco business through the customer segment lens, total Retail revenue grew by 2.6% to AUD19.3 billion.
We saw strong growth in Customer, up 3.6% to AUD10.3 billion -- sorry, in Consumer.
And also growth in Enterprise and Government up 4.4% to AUD4.3 billion.
Telstra Business declined slightly, down 0.9% to AUD4.7 billion reflecting the challenging economic environment for small and medium-sized businesses.
Wholesale declined 4.4% to AUD2.1 billion, mainly due to regulatory price changes, migration from resale products to lower ARPU infrastructure products, and declining PSTN usage.

Turning to Media; there are three aspects to our Media portfolio; Media Marketing Services, which is Sensis; Media Entertainment Services and Content, which includes BigPond, Content arrangements and the resale of Foxtel via Telstra; and finally, Foxtel itself.

David will talk a little later on the Sensis, but it has clearly been a challenging year, as it has been for many print businesses as we transition from print to a digital marketing services business.
Sensis revenue was down 17.7% to AUD1.5 billion with Print revenue down 22.1%, partly offset by growth in Digital, up 4.5%.
Notwithstanding the challenging year, Sensis' margins remained attractive, albeit declined 9 percentage points to 47%.
In Media Entertainment Services & Content revenue was up 4.7%.
This includes Foxtel sales vial Telstra up 3.1% to AUD602 million.
During the year, we also saw a number of positive signs that point towards the continued growth of this business.
We have now sold close to 400,000 T-boxes.
Over 5 million BigPond movies have been downloaded via the T-box since its launch.
There are now over 2.3 million billed transactions every month across the BigPond portfolio, including movies, music, games and shopping.
There have also been more than 600,000 downloads of the AFL app, and 8.1 million online video streams.
Let me now turn to Foxtel.
On a standalone basis, Foxtel revenues were up 3.6% in 2012 to AUD2.2 billion.
EBITDA was up strongly, 8.5% to AUD598 million.
These numbers exclude Austar which was acquired in late May.

Customer numbers were up 24,000 to 1.7 million, and Foxtel also saw improvements in the take-up of a number important products including Foxtel IQ, Multi-Room, and the high definition Digital offerings.
Penetration of Foxtel's IQ HD service increased from 31% to 42%, while over 80% of subscribers now take up Foxtel's sports package, and more than 40% take up the premium package.
Telstra's 50% economic interest in Foxtel is not consolidated into our results.
However, the distribution of AUD108 million received during the year was included in our EBITDA line.
Finally, turning to International.
International had a positive year, with revenue up 7% to AUD1.5 billion.
For CSL New World, our Mobile business in Hong Kong, revenue was up 5.7% to AUD860 million.
On a local currency basis, revenue was up 10% following strong customer growth, as David has mentioned, with new customer adds of 475,000.
This performance supported strong growth in CSL's EBITDA margin, up 4 percentage points to 26%.
While we saw a 27% decline in revenue in China, this largely followed the sale of SouFun in 2011, LMobile and ChinaM in 2012, as we refocused our portfolio on the successful Autohome business.
During the year, we also completed the Reach integration.
Following this, the global connectivity business grew 24.5% to AUD508 million.
The reintegration of Reach and the further expansion of our regional cable business provides an excellent platform from which for us to grow our domestic NAS business into the region.
I will now make a few comments on our ongoing productivity and simplification program.
During the year, direct variable costs increased approximately AUD300 million, due to increased mobile sales.

The impact of inflation was approximately AUD300 million, and other business growth, as a consequence of our growing portfolio and transaction volumes, increased expenses by approximately AUD400 million.
Expenses were also impacted by the fall in the Government bond rate, and impairments, and regulatory changes to mobile termination rates.
Against this, Project New delivered AUD1.1 billion in productivity benefits in 2012 with total operating expenses for the Group, including impairments, up only 0.8% to AUD15.3 billion.
Excluding impairments, operating expenses year on year were broadly flat.
A few comments on capital management.
In April, we presented to the market our strategic framework for capital management.
At that time, we indicated our excess free cash flow at the June 30, 2012 was expected to be between AUD0.5 billion to AUD1 billion.
We ended the year with excess free cash flow of AUD1 billion, at the top end of this range.
Against this, we have a significant debt refinancing program in 2013, and significant spectrum commitments.
Also, as you will hear from David shortly, we will be investing a further AUD500 million over the next two years to bring forward investments in our 4G mobile network, and the NBN transit networks.
This will extend our mobile network advantage, and bring forward the benefits from the NBN agreements.
These investments will increase our CapEx to sales ratio to approximately 15% per annum in 2013 and 2014.
This number is then expected to reduce below 14% in 2015.
We also indicated, in April, that we expected our excess free cash to grow to AUD2 billion to AUD3 billion over the next three years, subject to the timing of the NBN rollout.
This did not include the proceeds from the sale of TelstraClear, or the additional capital expenditure that I've just mentioned.

However, given our current capital position, and based on the NBN revised rollout that was announced yesterday, I can, nonetheless, confirm that our outlook for the next three years is still AUD2 billion to AUD3 billion.
The other parameters of our capital management framework remain unchanged, and Telstra is not contemplating capital management initiatives at this time.
Consistent with this framework, we continue to target a A credit rating, and all of the major credit rating agencies have recently confirmed this.
We are currently operating at the conservative end of our balance sheet parameters, with gearing at 53.2%, and debt servicing at 1.3 times.
In addition, we are carrying almost AUD4 billion of liquidity at June 30.
This positions us well for the significant debt refinancing program that I mentioned that we will be undertaking this year.
We have debt maturities of AUD3 billion in 2013, in addition to the spectrum commitments.
We have also been active in relation to our portfolio management as part of our overall capital management strategy.

Subject to the regulatory approval of TelstraClear, we will have raised approximately AUD660 million through the divestments of TelstraClear, LMobile and ChinaM in 2012, with most of this being redirected into a range of investment opportunities.
These included minority stakes in IPscape, dimmi, Mandoe and Ooyala, increasing our economic interest in Autohome, and finally, supporting Foxtel in its acquisition of Austar.
In summary, we finished the year in a strong capital position with a clear capital management framework and strategy, and a better performing portfolio of businesses.
Before closing, I would like to make a few comments on guidance for 2013.
As the decommissioning payments from the rollout of NBN will be treated as other income, we intend to guide based on total income in 2013 to capture these.
We have also included -- sorry, we have also excluded the impact of the sale of TelstraClear on guidance, and this includes the foreign exchange impairment expected to be released in 2013.
On this basis, we expect to see continued low, single-digit growth in both total income and EBITDA.
We expect our CapEx to sales ratio in 2013 to be approximately 15% as we support accelerated investments into our mobile network and the NBN transit network.
Free cash flow is expected to be between AUD4.75 billion and AUD5.25 billion, taking into account this additional capital expenditure.
Unlike previous years, the free cash flow guidance does not make any provision for investing CapEx; we will update guidance on free cash flow for investments if and when appropriate.

Finally, and subject to the Board's normal approval process for dividend declaration, and there being no unexpected material events, we expect to pay a fully-franked dividend of AUD0.28 per share in fiscal year 2013.
Before handing back to David, let me summarize.
2012 was a year of strong performance, delivering on our commitments and results, in line with guidance.
We achieved a standout performance in Mobiles with EBITDA up 21%, and 1.6 million new customers.
In Fixed retail broadband we added 203,000 new customers, and we grew revenues in NAS, up 10%, and International, up 7%.
Notwithstanding the continued decline in PSTN, as expected, an a very challenging year for Sensis, we delivered top line and bottom line growth in a relatively tough economic environment.
Project New delivered AUD1.1 billion of productivity benefits, and made a significant impact on improving our customer experience.
We have put in place a clear capital management framework, and have been actively managing our capital position, undertaking appropriate portfolio management.

We ended the year with excess free cash of AUD1 billion, and confirmed our outlook of AUD2 billion to AUD3 billion over the next three years, notwithstanding the revised NBN rollout announced yesterday.
And we expect the momentum in our business to continue into 2013.
Thank you, and I'll now hand back to David.
Thanks for that, Andy.

What I'm going to do now is just to go back to our strategic priorities and just give you a bit of an update on how we're going and some of the things I think are going to be important, as we go forward.
I may repeat a few of the things Andy's touched on, but I think it's important just to give you the perspective.

As you know, improving customer service, growing and retaining the number of our customers, really changing and simplifying the business, getting the complexity out, and then finding new growth businesses, is just what we focus on every day.
So what I'm going to do is just take you through each one of them and just give you a little bit more color on it.
So firstly, improving customer satisfaction.
Well, it is so core to any strategy, and we've got a lot to do.
But as you look across all the things we've done, as I mentioned, there are some real changes happening.
One area I'd like to highlight is the One Step initiative, which is really changing the way we actually activate services.
So if you imagine how imagine how many field engineers every day are out there doing work, getting greater efficiency in that, and a better customer experience, is very important.
So this is a one-step process for activating a PSTN voice service and an ADSL service.
For those who have moved house and had a different experience, this is actually really important.
And this means it's one truck roll, better customer experience.
As simple as that may sound, when you're doing literally hundreds of thousands of those every year, you get that right, a great experience.
That takes a lot of costs out, and makes a great customer experience.
Also we're seeing, like many other industries, real change in customer behavior and about how they want to interact with us.
Often, people are interested in contacting us between 10 o'clock and 12 o'clock at night, so we now need to provide a 24-hour a day, 7-day a week, service.

Interestingly, the use of social media is becoming a very popular way to interact with us, and also, things like use of Facebook and Livechat are really starting to change the dynamics of the way we support our customers.
As I mentioned before, we have 60 people also just monitoring social media sites, to find out where there's problems, so we can be more proactive.
This is a very different Telstra.

Also, we're finding that people want to get real-time information on how their mobile plan is performing, how their accounts are -- where they are in the month, and they often want to do it either from their mobile phone or from their tablet.
So we now have 13 mobile apps available in the market, and in fact one of -- the last one, I think, was the most popular mobile app for at least a month we put out there.
So these are real changes in the way we run the business and the way our customers want to interact with us.
And of course, we've had enormous redesign of our web pages, making them simpler, easier to use, and also with our online shop.
So we are seeing these improvements, as I mentioned before.
Level 1 TIO complaints are now down 26% in the year, and over the last three years has been down by over 30%.
So really significant changes, in terms of how our customers are interacting with us.
Also, as a result of all these improvements we've made, a very important statistic is actually the number of times our customers are calling us.
Of course, we want customers to call us when they need to buy something, but we prefer them not to have to call us about a question on the bill.
But we've seen our consumer call volumes decline by 21%.
We've never seen that sort of decline before, and that can only happen by delivering a better service.
Also, as I said before, we're introducing the Net Promoter system, and this is really another stage in really changing the culture at Telstra.
As I mentioned before too, we want to turn customers to advocates, not just giving them a great customer experience.
What we now do is measure as many transactions on a daily basis.
I get a multimedia message every morning.
It talks about all the transactions where we've had a survey on the previous day.
And that's usually about 20,000 bits of information that we have garnered feedback from our customers.
And they also give me a feel for whether they've been good experiences or bad experiences, or where the issue or the question's been resolved.
Interesting, I'd say this is probably the biggest change program we've ever put into Telstra.
Robert Nason is driving this.

I can't stress just how transformational it is, and it's not the things that you would see, looking at it externally, because it really touches every part of the business, whether in finance or legal, accounting, or you're in the front line.
Everybody's involved.
And it's a very simple principle that we adhere to.
We ask every Telstra employee to treat our customers the same way that they would like to be treated.
That's a big statement to make; and to give them the authority to do that is a big cultural change for the Company.
So a lot of work still to be done on that area.
For a Company like Telstra, with such high market share, this is not a nice-to-have.
It's really a mandate.
Secondly, retaining and growing the number of our customers.
And I do want to say, we're very grateful for the many customers who choose Telstra each year.
The quality of our mobile network is really helping to drive this growth, and I do believe, if you look right across the world, the network is becoming a key differentiator.
As Andy took you through, 1.6 million new domestic mobile customers were added, and that means over the last two years that's been 3 million new customers on our mobile network.
And that really is significant.
In September last year, we were the first Australian company to roll out LTE, the 4G network, also one of the first in the world to put it on the 1800 spectrum.
Now our 4G network covers more than 40% of the Australian population; I think it's 16 major towns, and another 20-odd rural towns.

But we need to maintain that network advantage because we're seeing such a strong demand for it, and very importantly, the LTE technology carries information about half the cost of previous technologies.
We will be investing AUD1.2 billion in fiscal 2, '13, as a part of this incremental capital investment that Andy mentioned before.
That's very important; mobility is a very critical part of our strategy.
Andy also mentioned we had very strong growth in Fixed broadband.
Now that particular portfolio is up 8.5% in revenue, and we also had very strong growth in our subscriber growth.
Also 336,000 customers signed up to bundled.
As you know, that's very important, because it's a two-year contract, and very importantly we keep really having aggressive set of products in the bundled area in the market.
So the total number of bundled customers is now 1.4 million.
Also, T-Box and T-Hub have done very well.
We've put the T-Hub version 2, an Android operating system in the new T-Hub2, and we saw very strong sales in '12.
This year, we sold 148,000 T-Hubs and 193,000 T-Boxes.
So IPTV remains very important, and I'll mention that a little bit more when I talk about the Media portfolio.
So all these products are NBN-ready, and really start to give a differentiated experience in the home.
Third area, simplifying the business.
This remains, and will always remain, a critical part of what we need to do.

Very importantly, we have seen this year a decline in our labor and labor substitution costs, and this has been driven by all the simplification efforts, productivity improvements, we're driving right across the business.
Now, I want to put this into context.
To drive a 1.8% decline in our labor and labor sub costs, while demand is growing, and we're trying to improve customers satisfaction, is really a very strong result.
And it is testament of the incredible dedication of our staff, right across the Company.
This is difficult to do, because volumes are up, and you've got to do things differently if you're going to be able to deliver that sort of productivity.
AUD1.1 billion in productivity benefits across the business, at a gross level, but that gives us the freedom to reinvest in new growth areas, move our resources to the new growth areas.
And this will continue to be a critical part of what we need to do, as we go forward.
Some interesting statistics; now 1.6 million access their bill digitally; that's whether they get a PDF one which is sent to them by e-mail or they access it on-line.
1 million customers have registered for direct debit, and we now receive over AUD100 million in online bill payments each month.
These are really big changes, and have shown really significant growth over the last 12 months.
Even the new online shop, which if you haven't tried it you should, it's a really great experience.
It's simple, easy to use, and that's how people are wanting to purchase.
And I mentioned before some of the new ways we're interacting with customers round Livechat, being on social media sites, it's really exciting to see the changes.
But we've only just begun.
We see really quite significant change over the next five years, as we really change the way we run the business to really be a digitally-led Company.
Now that's hard for a legacy -- a big corporation like Telstra, but we're making really good progress.
And then, of course, the fourth are is around our growth businesses.
Every element of that strategy's so important; Media, Asia, and Network Apps & Services, because these initiatives are really adjacencies.
They complement our core business, and if you can get it right, you both grow into new areas while still pulling through a lot of your core offerings in the market.
So let me go through each one of those.
Under the umbrella of our Media businesses, we recently announced some quite exciting new niches, with a company like MOG, which is a next-generation music company.
It's a partnership, and we think that this sort of partnership of innovation is going to be very important for us in the future.
That particular one delivers really good music services on smartphones, tablets and wireless hi-fi systems, but again, a great example of using innovation to really differentiate our offerings.
We think that partnering will be a critical part of the way we go forward.
Also, the acquisition by Foxtel of Austar was a key part of this growth strategy.
Also, the IPTV business is going well, and as you know, we announced a new executive to run that business, who's had deep media experience and has worked with (inaudible) previously before.
And we think that IPTV does play a very important part of the media landscape in the future.
I'm not saying it's everything, but it's a very critical part of where we're going in the future.
I'll come back to Sensis, because I've got a separate chart on Sensis; I want to give you a little bit of color about how that's going.
But before I do that, let me just turn to Asia and the Network & Apps Services business.

We're seeing some quite significant changes there, and it's good to see the collaboration from the area that Deena is working in, which is investing in new innovative technologies, and fitting into our growth businesses.
Just last month, we announced the investment in a New South Wales company, very innovative company called IPscape.
Now they provide Cloud-based call center solutions.
Not a lot of you picked up on it, but what is so strong about that product is it can be offered throughout Asia.
So Deena and Tariq are working strongly together to take that product into the international market, specifically Asia.
Also, Telstra Global.
Now Telstra Global is where we provide international services and managed network services is going very well.
That's international data and voice, satellite across Asia Pacific, China, India, Europe and Africa.
You may not know it, but we have 14 carrier licenses throughout Asia, 14 carrier licenses.

Now, I'm not saying we're going to set up an operation in each of those countries, but it's very important in terms of managing both Australian companies going offshore, but also servicing regional customers.
So we're very pleased with how the international portfolio is going.
They had 7% growth in product revenue last year.
CSL, in local currency terms, grew 10%.
And as you know, CSL has had some years of being better and some years not so good, but very strong results in Hong Kong.
And the global connectivity in NAS products, that I was just referring to, grew by 24.5% to a little bit over $0.5 billion.
Within the NAS business, I'm very pleased to say we've got a new leader in that Group.
Brendan's come in to run the whole operations area, but David Burns is now heading up the NAS business.
He comes with a lot of experience in this area, working in Europe, worked here in Australia, but this is a services business.
It has different characteristics to the core Telco business, but there's a very strong adjacency, and it's great to have David on the team.
We had a very strong sales result last year.
When you're talking about these big contacts, it's really the sales you do in the previous year that flow through in terms of revenue and profit in the subsequent years.
And it was the very strong bookings in the Enterprise Group led by Paul Geason did very well.

We have a very strong ambition to grow this throughout Asia, so Paul McManus, who was running that business, is now moving into Hong Kong to extend our capability throughout Asia with the NAS business.
So what you're seeing is these key growth portfolios working off each other to really drive differentiation.
So now let me come back to Sensis, because that has been a challenging business over the last couple of years.
I think we are getting through it.
We're absolutely confident the strategy is right.
When I talk to customers, they see the print to digital online world happening, but they want leadership.
They want someone to take them through that.
And I think that, as we move from being what -- we've called it yellow print to become a digital media marketing services company, that's a very big transition.

However, the relationship we have with the vast majority of small and medium businesses in Australia gives us a unique position that we need to now really prove to them that we can take them into the online world.
We're now into the second year of our digital sales, and across the -- we have these canvases, we're starting to see some really good response.
They like the product, and really importantly, the sales cycle has shortened significantly.

When we started nearly -- well, it would have been nearly 12 months ago, the sales cycle is quite long because they were used to buying a print product, and now we had to explain to them how AdWords works with Google, how we're going to render them across various search engines.
But now they're getting more familiar with that, we're starting to get a better response rate.
And also, we've got to re-tool that business.
To get a 47% EBITDA was a very strong result, and great testament to the very hard work that's going on in that business.
We now have John Allan, who has joined us to lead Sensis, and John has rich media experience, and you really do need media experience to run that business now.
No longer could we take a traditional Telstra executive and put them in there; we really need to build our online and digital experience in our executive ranks.
And I'm pleased to say he's just arrived; got a lot ahead of him.
But I think we're confident we can really make a difference, as we go forward.
So we're now a year into the three-year transition.
We do still expect -- as I said, it's a three-year transition.
There will be double-digit decline in revenues next year.
And then by '14 and '15, we think we'll start to see some stabilization.
But we're not through it yet, so we've still got a lot of work to do.
So let me now summarize before we can take questions.
First thing I want to say is that we've delivered on our commitments, and that's so important for us in terms of credibility.
We've met guidance; our business is proving resilient, because it's a big portfolio; and of course, the balance sheet remains very strong.
So it does give us flexibility, as we look to the future.
Our strategic priorities are delivering.
Top and bottom line growth is very important to us, and we expect the business to continue to grow at the top and bottom line in full-year '13.
And of course, consistency of strategy is important, and we're not changing our strategy at this time.
We'll be very happy to take any questions.
I'll ask Ben to come up and to just host that.
So thanks very much.
Thank you, David and Andy.
We've got plenty of time for questions this morning.
We will as ever start, for those of you who have come here in Melbourne, and then we will take some questions from the phone lines a little bit later.
Mobile obviously very strong.
If you break it down into the different segments, Enterprise and Government's double digit, Consumer's double digit, but Business Services are lagging well behind, about 2.8% growth.

And I wonder what's going on there, because you think with what's going on generally in Mobile and the capabilities in Mobile broadband, that would be an ideal set of products in the business segment.
You said, back in February at the results, that you were seeing difficulties in monetizing data.
I think you were talking more generally than necessary mobiles, but I wonder is that still the case?
Is there some turn around there, and what have you done?
What can you do to achieve that?
And if might also, just one question for Andy?
With your guidance, you qualified the guidance to say it's subject to stable regulatory prices.
I think you had a footnote to that effect.

But the key access prices are set in concrete, as I understand, for three years, ULL, wholesale DSL, wholesale line rental, so I wonder why you feel the need to qualify that, and is there something else on the horizon we should be aware of?
Ian, look, your observation is absolutely right.
In the business sector, the Mobile's growth wasn't as strong, primarily driven by ARPU decline.
We had very high ARPUs in that market, and it was pretty competitive.
I know Will and the team have been working hard there.
We've seen good momentum coming out of the year as we rebalance the pricing.

And of course, to your point around data, they are related, because the consumption of mobile data plans, as a lot of small businesses are using it to interact with mail, etc., is a mix we've got to get right.
We've had a bit of competition in that part of the market, so as we've pulled ARPU down, we're starting to see the momentum, or the prices down, then we come back.
With think there's opportunity for '13, but, yes, it's been a more challenged segment.

But I think that some of the strategies around bundling around the digital business product, in the way we're interacting mobility with the IP service, will give us some nice differentiation, going forward.
But your point's right; we've got more work to do.
It was not the highlight of the year, but I truly recognize it.
The data question mobility is a bigger question.
As you've seen, there's quite a bit of change around the world as people are moving towards data plans and how you manage that in terms of the structure of your plans.
Luckily, we've been pretty good at managing that transition.
Remember SMS declines globally; we've not seen that because we always had included SMS.
So Kate and the team are doing a good job at managing through that, but we can give you more detail later.
So I'll let you maybe -- just the one on the guidance side, [Andy].

No, look there's nothing specific in that exclusion on guidance; it's just basically the same guidance we've always given, which is that to the extent that there are regulatory determinations which we are not aware of today, i.e., those that we are aware of today are included in our guidance, but if there are regulatory determinations during the course of the year that we're not aware of today, we will adjust for those when we actually come to our final result.
Ian, there is a little bit more on that.
We have the IAD on the wholesale ADSL pricing.
We're still waiting for the FAD.
And that's probably, Tony, end of the year?
So that is one that is still not completely got a bow round it.
Okay, a couple of questions; the first one on operating costs.
You did flat underlying costs this year.
I'm just wondering if you can talk a little bit about productivity savings into FY '13 and the potential for cost growth or decline in that year.
And the second one is just around LTE.
I know it's early days, but I'm just wondering if you could give us a little of the sense of usage patterns, ARPU and maybe cost savings on those customers, relative to your 3G customers?
And just thirdly, Foxtel; Richard Freudentstein's been talking about offering broadband as a triple play into the future.
I just wanted to get your thoughts around how you view that.
It's obviously something that hasn't really been discussed too much in the past, how you look at that, going forward.
Yes, okay, I'll try to cover all three, and I'll ask Andy to give a few comments on productivity.
Our productivity aspirations are about the same full year '12.
We need to keep driving that and both capital efficiency, as well as underlying simplification of the business to get, somewhere in the legacy areas, our operating costs down.
And Robert and the team continue to run a very strong cross-Company program and working with Gordon and Brendan about how we can really drive greater efficiency.
So the scale is about the same.
Always a question here about reinvesting in the growth businesses, and that's the trade off we make.
But it will be about the same sale, we think, as '12.
That's what you should probably look to plan for.
(inaudible) flat costs --?
Yes, in that area.
LTE, the ARPUs are a little bit higher, but the costs are a lot lower.
The thing about LTE, it's a far greater, far better efficient technology.
So as I say, it's about 50% less than what we would get on the 3G network.
And we teamed -- it's very early days, because people who adopt early tender to be the higher ARPU customers anyway.
So we've not seen -- we're not into the millions, we're at just on 400,000-odd, actually 375,000.
So it's early days and, of course, some of the people are taking dongles as well, or the Wi-Fi device, where you've got that, which nets a higher ARPU.
So we're a little bit reticent to put out too much data until we get to about 1 million subs or so, but it's encouraging; it's encouraging, is the best way to say it.
Okay and number three, Foxtel; Foxtel have always had the ability to the triple play.
People ask me this question often.
And it's purely a financial issue for Foxtel.
We have always said that when you need to do it, you can do it.
Obviously, we would have to put a competitive tender into them if they hopefully use or services, but that's not a given.
They run independently, in that sense.
But, yes, I think that, just like BSkyB has done it in the UK, I think there's an opportunity for Foxtel to do that.
And we'll continue to look at what's the right thing for Foxtel, because that's our responsibility to get the best returns in that asset.
So that's where we're at with that one.
Could I just have a follow-up question?
You talked about IPTV as being important.
How important is selling Foxtel's services through the T-Box as part of your vision there?
It sounds like it's been relatively slow and you don't seem to push it very hard.
Yes, well, it has been slow.
We're really trying to get the experience as good as we can.
Putting all those services through our ADSL 2 services, it's pretty good on HFC and, depending where you are, on the copper.
No, it's very important.
Remember, we think that Pay TV, paying for content, is a critical part of any media strategy.
Within IPTV, you can do some things differently, interactivity, how you structure the screen, and that's what we're going to be doing a lot of work on.
But we're also partnering very closely with Foxtel on that.
And we'll work through the product offerings, but no, very important.
Remember Pay TV in Australia is only at, what, 28%/29% of homes have a Pay TV service.
There's still a lot of growth.
The issue has been it's quite a high ARPU product, but we're trying to -- I think you'll see some changes.
And Richard's already alluded to that in terms of improving penetration this year.
Mark McDonnell, BBY.
Two areas I'd like to ask you about.
The first is Mobiles and the second is on your revenue guidance.
Firstly, with regards to Mobiles, I was wondering if you could split out the 375,000 4G sales into those that are mobile broadband versus those that are handsets?

And if you can't give us exact numbers, if you could give us, perhaps, an indication of trend, i.e., does the higher speed of 4G translate to a higher proportion of broadband wireless connects, relative to your underlying base?

But the broader issues associated with your reinvestment strategy in Mobiles to support the growth that you're enjoying relates to your views now about the adequacy of your spectrum, particularly in the light of Bill Morrow's comments that Vodafone may well not pursue the digital dividend spectrum; Optus' acquisition of Vividwireless and a considerable enhancement of their spectrum assets?

And whether, in the light of that, you believe that you have sufficient spectrum, given the share that you have, the growth that you're enjoying and your relative positive vis-a-vis your competitors and, therefore, what impact that might have on your funding expectations with respect to the spectrum?
And the last component of that first question is, then, with respect to the debt funding that's proposed on that.
I know that's been said a number of times, but what we haven't heard is in respect of a 15-year license, whether you would pay back that debt at the rate of amortization?
Or whether you see this as a permanent change to your gearing?
Right, okay, Mark.
So let me handle the first ones, and I'll get Andy to talk to the debt funding on the spectrum.
So we did break out, on the 375,000 4G devices, 113,000 were handsets, and so the rest will be dongles or the MiFi device.
And that's meant we've only got two handsets in the market, the HTC and the Samsung.
But we're pretty pleased with that result; a lot better than we had actually anticipated.
I think that answers that one.
Now, in terms of broadband wireless connectivity and is that having -- I think you're question is, it having an impact on the fixed environment?
Well, we did see a 2% growth in the number of wireless -only households this year.
I don't really know yet, Mark.
It's early days.
If you looked at those numbers, you'd say of the 375,000, there is more obviously wireless broadband users on the LTE.
But I don't think that, at least at the moment, I'm ready to extrapolate that out further.
But a 2% growth is higher than we've seen.
Usually we've got about 1%, so that has accelerated.
Now spectrum, that's a complex question.
Is spectrum important to us?
Are we comfortable where we are with spectrum?
Well, absolutely we are.
Our engineers were the first to look at re-farming of 1800.
I know the digital dividend's coming up, and we'll talk to that in a moment.
And also, we had an opportunity to do 2300 TD-LTE.
But we're comfortable where we are, because it's not just spectrum, you need spectrum, the mobile network, and you need devices in the market.
Now, the Chinese are unquestionable pushing TD-LTE and they're becoming a big market, as you know.
However, you've got to have the whole eco system right, and that's what we look to and pick the timing on when you bring that product to market.
Now, we also have some access to those higher in spectrum, if wanted to, but we're pretty comfortable with where we are.
But that's not to belie the point; it is very important us managing that spectrum; it is going to be very important as we go forward.
Also remember, the digital dividend isn't available still for a couple of years, so we've got to really free up the spectrum and move forward.
But at the moment, we're pretty comfortable with where we're are.
I'm aware of any comments made, but I'm focused on where we're seeing growth and where we can get good returns; that's what we do.
Okay, does that give you a bit of sense?
We can pick it up later; it's a (inaudible) to the discussion.
David, just on the financing point, so what we've said in the context of capital management, is that we will basically fund spectrum out of debt.
That doesn't, though, necessarily go as far as to say that we will then also amortize that debt in line with the spectrum lifetime.
It's just from the point of view of setting a framework for excess free cash that we have in the short to medium term.
So just to be clear on that, Andy, you're saying that there's no plans to reduce that debt over the 15 year period?
Sorry, to be clear, Mark, so there's no plans to increase our gearing.
Just in the short to medium term we will fund the spectrum acquisitions out of debt and we will, obviously, maintain our gearing levels within our balance sheet settings, which is 50% to 70%.
But essentially, it's not a permanent increase to debt.
Mark, there's 10 more people waiting to ask questions, so can you make your second question one question?
The question will be brief.

I'm hoping you can help decompose your revenue guidance, particularly the proportion of uplift associated with the recent price rises, particularly taking demand -- price elasticity of demand effects into account, and the degree to which the slower rollout of the NBN is a decrement to your revenue outlook?
I think I'll ask my modeler to comment on that one (laughter).
I think the short answer is no, sorry Mark, we won't provide a breakdown.
Obviously, we're providing guidance at the total level of low single digit.
But Mark, I can say on our first cursory look at the NBN rollout, there's no material impact forecast.
We've got three more questions here in Melbourne, and then we'll go to the phone lines.
Raymond Tong, Goldman Sachs.
Just three questions.
Firstly, just in terms of your mobile margins, you got up to about 39% in the second half.
Just wondering where you see that trending in the next year or so?
And can you maybe just discuss the trends that you see happening in terms of re-contracting new customer mix, going forward?
Secondly, can you maybe discuss, have you see any economic slowdown across your Consumer business and Enterprise segments?
And just the last one, is just in terms of your FY '13 guidance.
Now I just want to confirm whether that includes or excludes the TelstraClear impairments?
Shall I just knock over that last one first?

So to be clear we're excluding all of TelstraClear from guidance, so assume take it out of 2011 -- sorry 2012, take it out of 2013 and that goes both for the operating numbers as well as the impairments.
Okay, do you want to do number one on the Mobile margin as well?
Well, I think, David, you've been on the record in the past as saying that, over the medium term, we expect to see mobile margins in the high 30%.
So 39% in the second half of the year is what we would aim to be seeing over the medium term.
Yes, so we think that's where we should be and that's where our plans are at the moment.
So let me go through, so re-contracting, yes, there's a little bubble coming our way, as we know.
And we've done a lot of work in this area, as you'd expect.
Obviously, it's a bit dependent on a bit of an overhang in the market around when the iPhone 5 is going to arrive, so like any good operator, we're very diligently getting ready for that.
But I'm confident that we're well placed in the re-contracting.
It is a little bit higher this year, but remember it is all about how you re-contract.
And there's new ways that Gordon and the team are looking at, and I think that we've got some good approaches there.
I think that's what I'll leave with today, because it's a bit sensitive.
Now in terms of the economy, if you look at our results while there's some puts and takes on some accounting on the Mobile results, the second half was a little bit slower.
I think that's just reflecting the pretty choppy different sectors across the retail set.
We've seen continued performance in the last couple of months, but it is down from where it was seven months ago, but I don't think it's of any great significance.
We're watching it very closely; our churn levels are still very low, and the take up of bundles is strong.

And as you know, we have put the price increases in to the market, but we think that if those who want to take a bundle, it's still a really good offer, but if you're still on old PSTN service then you get a bit of an increase.
So far so good, but it is definitely a little slower.
Then the last one was --
Guidance.
Guidance and we've covered it.
Okay, good thank you.
Andrew Anagnostellis, Deutsche Bank.
Just two questions.

Following up from the Mobile discussion, you saw a slowdown, 2.8% growth in the postpaid Mobile markets, just wondering if that's tough comps or anything else happening there, obviously offset by the prepaids, perhaps if you can talk to the mix there?

And just a second question; I take onboard your comments on Sensis having another difficult year, but it looks a Herculean task when you've got 4% growth in Digital and 20% plus decline in Print, what gives you confidence you can stabilize the business?
And just at the bigger picture, why is Telstra, as a Group, committed to this business when it's clearly a tough industry for everyone?
Yes, well, I'll cover that one while it's at the top of mind, do you offer (laughter)?
AT&T might.
That's the reality, we have to if -- actually the more we look at it, and Rick and I have spent a lot of time on it, we think there's some real opportunity.
But it is going to be difficult, and I don't want to leave you with the impression that we've got it all covered.
But the strategy that we're on is unique, and we do know all the other yellow operators around the world.
Some have done well, some have been more challenged and some people have decided to get out.
2.5 times EBIT doesn't sound very good to us, and as we've restructured the business we looked at the three-year plan, where we get to.
And if it is truly an online business, it actually has more value than it does today.
That's the strategy; the execution is going to be difficult.
But the signs we've had in the last three months to four months have been encouraging, but not victory encouraging.
If we can hold the customer base, move them to the digital product, then we think there's a future for that business, but it is what it is, and that's that.
So that's that one.
Now in terms of the Mobile business itself, yes, the growth was slower in the second half; there's a number of factors for that, but we have still seen good growth.
Remember the half -- it's a half to half comparison, end of full year '11 was a very strong half as well, so we've got that comparison.
But we're still seeing that we'll grow faster than the market, as we go forward, and we think that momentum will continue.
It is going to be dependent on when this iPhone 5 will -- will be a bit of a jab in the arm, I think, for the industry.
So we've got to be well prepared for that, which we think we are.
And it's been very gratifying to see the growth in prepaid.
I remember Gordon standing up here and saying one of his must-win battles was to be number one in prepaid, and I think we now are.
And we've never been there in all my years at Telstra, and we're still seeing good profitability coming out of that sector.
So while it's actually declined, we're actually doing very well, very pleased with the performance in that area.
And then as we continue to drive LTE and the 4G, we see a strong year ahead of us.
But I don't think it's going to be as good as '12, okay.
Do you want to make a comment Gordon?
It's fair to say I think all of the analysts would predict that the market is slowing next year.
And the challenge will not be the underlying growth in the market overall; it's around the value you create from a slowing Mobiles market.
If you look at any global market you see the same trends occurring, so our aim is to continue to win market share, and we're well positioned to continue to win market share.
We've taken market share across all of our Mobile categories this year.

We've also seen a 3 points improvement of our Mobile profitability, and we know there's still some upside and underlying Mobile profitability, if we look at many of the global benchmarks around the world as well.
So I think next year is all about value creation and underlying profitability and growth in those particular attributes of our overall Mobile product set, and that's what we're aiming to achieve.
The last question from Melbourne, at the moment.
Richard Eary, UBS.
Just two questions; the first one was on M&A.
I think that, at the first half results, you identified a number of areas that you were looking at.

Publicly, you've come out and, obviously, knocked a couple of those over; could you give us a feel in terms of whether there's anything material, sizeable that you're looking at on a 18 months' view, or whether you can update us in terms of how you're looking at the M&A space?
So that's the first one.
The second for Andy in terms of guidance; the cash flow guidance for '13 can you just give us an update in terms of pension contributions within that guidance, and also the NBN proceeds?
I think, in April, you said you expected AUD1 billion of NBN cash proceeds to come through in '13 and '14, I just wondered whether you could give us an update on the split?

And then on guidance for your AUD2 billion to AUD3 billion of excess cash flow which you've maintained, despite the increase in CapEx, could you just give us a feel in terms of where you think -- obviously that's a slight upgrade, where you're a bit more comfortable, or where you're a bit more positive within the underlying business?
Do you want me to go through the last ones first; it's the longer one of the two, in reverse order.

So the AUD2 billion to AUD3 billion, so I guess since April what's occurred is that firstly, we've finished 2012 at the top end of our range that we indicated for 2012, which was AUD500 million to AUD1 billion, so we were at the top end of the range there, that's AUD1 billion.

And also, of course, we've announced the sale of TelstraClear which assuming that it completes, as we fully expect it to do, will add another AUD640 million in cash proceeds against which we will be investing AUD500 million.
So they're the sort of upsides if you like, Richard, which give us the comfort to be able to reconfirm that.
Obviously, we've only just seen the new NBN plans, so we've only had a quick look at that, but as David indicated, we don't see any significant variance of that over the whole transaction.

To the guidance point in relation to 2013 revenue, in relation to updating in update pension contributions, all I would say is that there is no expectation that they will either be more or less in 2013, relative to 2012, so there's no significant change there.

As regards the NBN proceeds, I'm not going to break it down, but suffice is to say that, of the AUD1 billion that I spoke to the market about in April, as you can imagine the majority of that, or the large proportion of that was in 2014, not 2013 at that time in any event, just because what we were expecting in relation to the rollout.
In relation to M&A, Richard, our strategy is the same.
We're already focused on acquiring capability where we need it, bolt-ons around the core, and new, innovative technologies like the investments in Ooyala which was on the West Coast.
That's our focus for now, and I think pretty much that will be, going forward.
We scan the markets pretty aggressively these days, because we do need to stay abreast of the changes in the industry, and as the convergence continues to take place.
But there's nothing on the horizon, at this time, but if we do change that position we will let you know, but that's our position today.
We'll now go to the telephones.
Justin Diddams.
Just a couple of questions from me; firstly, just on Mobile.
So that 39% margin in the second half, cracking result, I was wondering if you could give it some color about where the cost -- what happened in the cost base there?
Obviously there's not much detail in the notes.
And just one more specifically around the cost of goods sold and the cost of handsets, and really what drove the margin beat their first?
Second question just on CapEx of 15%.
If we look at global Telco players, 15% to 16% seems to be the norm at the moment, I was wondering why you think CapEx will drop back to 14% in FY '15?
And then thirdly, a bit of a dorky question, just around interest expense, I was wondering if you could give us sort of a read on what you think the interest charge will be for FY '13?
Obviously, there was quite a step down in FY '12.
That'll do it.
Right, I'm going to let Andy handle all three, and then I'll make one comment on the CapEx to sales at the end.
Well, I think firstly, in relation to the margin on Mobiles, as I said previously in response to another question that David was given, I think our view, our aspiration is to be at the high 30%.
So as you say, 39% in the second half was a cracking result, and I wouldn't say that we'd be predicting that completely into the future, but that's our aspiration to be at or around that level.

I think what underlies that is, obviously, the strong growth in Mobiles that we have achieved on the one hand, in conjunction with the productivity benefits that we've achieved on the other through the Project New, through moving a lot of the transactions online, a lot of service aspects online as well.
So I think it's been sort of on both sides, if you like, of the P&L account.
On the CapEx to sales ratio, why do we think it will reduce below 14% in 2015 is because that's what we're planning to make it do.

So it maybe needs a bit more color, but the point is that we've maintained that our CapEx to sales ratio, in the context of our capital management strategy and framework, is around 14% CapEx to sales.

We believe that it is a sensible thing for us to do, to take advantage of our strong capital position at the moment to invest in the acceleration of the rollout of LTE, to continue to invest in our mobile network.

By the way, I don't know if you picked up from what David said, that will bring our total investment into the Mobile network in 2013 to AUD1.2 billion, just in 2013, as well as enable us to accelerate our investment in the NBN network.
That, therefore, means that's expense or CapEx that is accelerated, and therefore, by definition, if it's accelerated it should enable us to reduce what we would have otherwise spent in 2015.
So I think that's the answer.
As regards interest cost and where that's likely to go, I guess if you could tell me what's going to happen with global interest rates I'll give you that answer.

But maybe to put a bit more color into that, I think our net interest cost this year was 7%, global interest rates don't look as though they're -- there's a lot of pressure on the upside at the moment, so I'm not expecting anything radically different next year.
I might just add a couple of small comments.
One of the areas that I think I would also attribute to the strong performance in Mobiles is Warwick Bray and the team have done an outstanding job in really managing.
The clarity you need around [SARX], around just how we are managing that mix, that does have a big impact.
And also, we're doing a lot of work around reducing the cost, both to activation of mobiles, how to do that differently.
And it's allowing us to get some cost out, but also some very active management, I think, right across the portfolio, but as you know, it's a complicated business when you get underneath it.
So yes, the 14%, it's, it is a tough call; I think you're right, Justin.
Because in our industry, you've got to keep investing; you've got to keep ahead of the technology curve.
But also, I think Andy and the senior team also believe that we can be more efficient in the capital we spend.
And that's a difficult one, because you've got multiyear projects, and we're going to trial some really different ways the way we manage our big projects and our capital spend.
So that's what we're going for, and we've started a big body of work, and that's what we're going to manage to.
But I'm not saying that also is going to be easy, but I think it's the right thing to do.
Daniel Blair, Nomura.

Interesting, the momentum in the Enterprise business, and in Consumer, was still very strong coming out of the year.

So that set's us up, I think, better as we come into this year.
The NAS portfolio has signed a number of deals; Andy mentioned those as well.
And there's a number of very large transactions that will be decided in the next six months that give us quite a degree of confidence in terms of that trajectory.
It's interesting, we are seeing, in the Enterprise space, a strong push to use technology to drive costs out, and that's across a number of sectors.
So the focus on technology being a product innovator is really starting to bear real fruit.
So mobility, as we alluded to, grew fast in the market.
There's no question, as Gordon said, and I said, it's slow but it's still going well; fixed broadband very strong coming out of the year.
So when you put it all together, we have a good degree of confidence about our growth trajectories.
Now in terms of Sensis, and I hope I've got the questions correct.
I think firstly, the revenue decline, EBITDA decline, roughly about the same in terms of their scale for the full year, '13 year.

Customer retention and growth is probably a critical, critical, component, because if you can hold the relationship with a customer and prove to them that you can take them into the digital world, then I think we've got a stronger future ahead of us.
I'm sorry, Daniel, the third part of your question was it '14/'15 Sensis?

Our expectations in -- '13 will be a -- the rate of decline will slow, as will in '14 and, hopefully, by '15, will be starting to flatten out.
That's the plan of record as much as we can give to you.
And we're going to try, as you do, you've got to set your targets and manage to them.
Rick, do you want to make any other comments on that, or -- I think that's probably enough, yes.
So that's it Daniel, I hope that gives you some flavor.
That's great.
Thanks again, guys.
Sameer Chopra, Merrill Lynch.
I have three quick questions, all on costs.

Or do you see potential for more chunky cost out coming through in FY '13?

COGS as a percentage of sales, your expectations for next year, would you see this ratio going up or down?

It's just the size of this business and the opportunity, be it in the operations area, in activation, the complexity of the handoffs we've created, even in the new IP products.
We were spending, I think, it was nearly four to five months to do a IP telephony.
And the end-to-end process, we've got a lot of opportunity to take cost out and improve, going forward.
So there is a lot of opportunity there.
In terms of productivity and headcount, I have been on record, we will continue to manage that aggressively, and where there are more opportunities to drive the business more efficiently.
But it's really a rebalancing, of moving from very large legacy parts of the business had a lot of headcount, and moving them in to the new growth areas.
But there's still more to do as we go forward [with that].
So let me throw it to Andy and he can talk to you COGS as a percentage of sales and also depreciation.

Our CapEx spend over the last couple of years was up 5% this year, relative to last year.
And it will be up a little bit, as we've just talked about, because of the additional investments we're making next year.
But that's not going to have a material impact to the D&A line.
I think the other key point on the COGS to sales is that, in these very large contracts you sign, you do have a little bit of cost up front over a 10-year period.
And that's probably pushing our COGS up a little bit higher.
But overall, it's still a good business to be in.
Digby Gilmour, CLSA Limited.

Andy, you indicated that the PSTN declines are in line with your expectations.

(inaudible).

So I'll let Andy answer the first one, and I'll do the NAS one.
Is that okay?

The NAS business, the rate of growth did decline in the second half but, again, there was quite a large one-off transaction in the previous six month period, so the underlying growth was actually very strong.
Also, the number of big sales we had was NAB, Department of Human Services, Australia Post, Origin, they are very big contracts that kick through into '13.
Obviously, as the business grows, double-digit growth gets harder, but we still see double-digit growth, going forward, and we remain enthusiastic about that business.
Now in terms of margin, you're right to point that out, because margin is what is critical in a services business.
It's less capital intensive, more labor intensive, therefore methodology and efficiency is really important.

Now the reason that we don't often talk about NAS is that the margin is -- it actually is spread right across the [op c] area, and we actually leverage a lot of our existing capability, so it becomes an allocation method.
But over the next 12 to 18 months, we'll give you more and more clarity as we just really focus in on that business.
And remember, it is about how you put the services and the carriage together to deliver the service to the customers and we look at the margin across both, so that's the critical nature of that.

We think we've got opportunity, good opportunity, and the plan is to improve our margin year to year as we go forward, as we bring on these contracts, drive very strong, what we call delivery towers, driving efficiency and better solutioning at the front end of the business.
But we can pick that up with you separately.
We've come a long way in that business, which is good.

David, maybe to add as well, looking at Paul Geason here, because that's putting Paul under too much pressure, I think the other point to make is that as we sit here today, the proportion of our outlook and target for 2013 that is incumbent in existing contracts which have been signed, because of those big contracts being signed is, it's a bigger proportion than it was this time last year, which augers well for next year.
Bradley Clibborn, Credit Suisse.

Gordon, do you want to comment anything more?

The only thing I'd say is one of the great shifts we've achieved this financial year is the quality of the mix of customers we're bringing on board, given the quality of the network and introduction of LTE where we see, if you look to year ago, we would have had, for price plans below AUD59, we would have had about -- in FY '11 we had about 34% of our customers above the AUD59 price point and above.
If we look at FY '12, we're now at about 71%, so what we see is an improvement in quality of customer.
What we see is an improvement in the quality of the mix and the plan mix.
We're seeing an improvement in the usage and customers wanting more inclusions because they're using data more.
And we're beginning to monetize that and that, actually, is reaping greater margin improvement and we don't see that abating.
So that's why the margin improvement is sustainable, notwithstanding as we shift to a year of re-contracting with the launch of iPhone 5.
So that's a positive trend that we want to --
And (inaudible) question?
I must just get Mark Hall to answer the question on (multiple speakers) and cash CapEx.

What we've had this year is a program managed on a far more flatter basis, i.e., even keel across the year, so we don't have that same impact and we'd expect that to continue, going forward.

LTE and our investment in that, we're going to continue to really invest in building out the mobile network so we're really delivering a differentiated experience; an experience where people can be rely on it, great data speed so they get to use all those wonderful applications.

Probably not quite as big as 1.6 million, because that was a pretty strong year -- we've done that for two years -- but still very strong as we go forward.

As Gordon said before, if you were in the room, it's been very gratifying to see how people appreciate the strength of the network, a service that works well, reliable, fast data speeds and doesn't drop out.

John Durie.

So once stage 2 (inaudible - microphone inaccessible).

As Sensis is adjusting, we've put more effort into those sort of areas of the Company, so we're just now expanding the breadth of what was in the original Project New scope.

And John, the only other thing I'd add to Robert's comments, as we are reengineering the business across the multiple silos, you've got to change the network and a lot of your IT systems that actually take sometimes years to get through.
And as Robert is saying, as you go deeper into the business you see more opportunities to do things differently.
Also, to use different technologies.
We're using a lot of web-based technology now; rather than changing core systems, we're doing it at the front end.

Mitchell Bingemann, The Australian.

That's simple, thanks.
Right.

David Fickling, Bloomberg.
Just a couple of things.

Voice, like many markets around the world, is flat to slightly up; it's that sort of level.

Though, interestingly, the number of minutes that people spoke on the mobile phone last year was up 25%.
So people are using their mobile phone a lot.
But, obviously, because we've got these pretty much all-included voice calls and SMS.
But data's the big growth area.
Wireless broadband, as you saw now, over 3 million users.
That's a lot.
Jeff, the Herald Sun.
I was just interested, back on the price rises we saw in July for postpaid, I believe one analyst remarked that Telstra's looking expensive again.
And I was actually just wondering, are you not afraid to alienate, I suppose, some segments of the market you've made gains in, in order to regain some of that margin.
And also, within the industry broadly, are we seeing an end to that, I suppose the price war going downwards that we've seen for the previous years?
We've very, very focused, as I said, in our strategic priorities; customer service and customer growth.
So we are not doing anything that is going to impact our aspirations about increasing the number of customers we have.
However, like any business, we've got to look at where people are getting value and how we can maximize our return to shareholders while still giving a competitive offer.
Now, across the portfolio it's a little bit different, and it depends on where your competitors are at.
But, in general, we're not too bad.
But, again, it's got to be the experience, what we include in the bundle, the service; it's many other factors as well.
We just don't want this to be a price-driven market.
We want it to be a quality market where people get really good experience.
I don't know if you saw, but a lot of the premium brands are doing very well around the world, are getting great value creation.
This is in the high-end fashion area.
That's quite unusual.
So we do think there's an opportunity for us to really offer a compelling experience.
However, always will be about increasing the number of customers we have, and that's the balance point we've got.
Wait and see how we go.
But we're not going to let that -- if we see it dropping down, we will do something else.

With the success of your AFL streaming service, will you be -- with the NRL rights, which are being negotiated, will you be looking for the same type of arrangement, or would that product be housed in Foxtel?

But do we see it as important?

Just a little aside, John, we were in the US recently.
This Ooyala product, a company we invested in, what it does is tracks people's consumption of content.

And how you manage that consumption of content across multiple screens, because that's how people want to do it, is a really exciting area and changing very quickly.
That's what we're working on at the moment (multiple speakers).
